output.text:
Looking at the code fragments, I can see that the `hexi` library provides a `conditional_reverse` template function for compile-time endianness conversion. For the runtime version, I need to implement the logic to handle different endianness combinations at runtime.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/endian.h>
#include <cstdint>
#include <bit>

template<std::endian from, std::endian to, typename T>
T convert_endianness(T value) {
    return hexi::conditional_reverse<from, to>(value);
}

template<typename T>
T convert_endianness_runtime(T value, std::endian from, std::endian to) {
    if (from == to) {
        return value;
    }

    // Need to perform byte swap
    if constexpr(std::is_same_v<T, float>) {
        return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint32_t>(value)));
    } else if constexpr(std::is_same_v<T, double>) {
        return std::bit_cast<T>(std::byteswap(std::bit_cast<std::uint64_t>(value)));
    } else {
        return std::byteswap(value);
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`convert_endianness`**: This compile-time version uses the `hexi::conditional_reverse` template function, which takes the source and destination endianness as template parameters and conditionally performs the byte swap only when needed.

2. **`convert_endianness_runtime`**: This runtime version:
   - First checks if the source and destination endianness are the same; if so, returns the value unchanged
   - For floating-point types (`float` and `double`), it uses `std::bit_cast` to convert to the appropriate unsigned integer type, performs the byte swap, then casts back
   - For integral types, it directly uses `std::byteswap`

This implementation follows the same pattern shown in the `conditional_reverse_inplace` function from the hexi library code fragments.

