```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

struct UserData {
    uint32_t user_id;
    std::string name;

    void serialise(auto& stream) {
        stream << user_id << name;
    }
};

void serialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, const UserData& data) {
    // Call the object's serialise method with the writer stream
    const_cast<UserData&>(data).serialise(writer);
}

void deserialize_object(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader, UserData& data) {
    // Use the reader's >> operator to deserialize the data
    reader >> data.user_id >> data.name;
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **`serialize_object`**: This function calls the `serialise()` method on the `UserData` object, passing the `binary_stream_writer`. The `serialise()` method uses the `<<` operator to write `user_id` and `name` to the stream. Note: We need to use `const_cast` since `serialise()` is not marked as `const` but we receive a `const UserData&`.

2. **`deserialize_object`**: This function uses the `binary_stream_reader`'s `>>` operator to read data back into the `UserData` object's fields. Since the `serialise()` method uses `<<` (which is for writing), we use the complementary `>>` operator for reading the same fields in the same order (`user_id` then `name`).

This approach follows the pattern shown in the Hexi examples where:
- `<<` is used for serialization (writing)
- `>>` is used for deserialization (reading)
- The order of fields must match between serialization and deserialization

