   - Relative positioning (`buffer_seek::current`)
   - End-relative positioning (`buffer_seek::end`)

3. **`update_header_at_position`**: Demonstrates a common use case for write seeking:
   - Saves the current write position
   - Writes a placeholder header (zeros)
   - Writes body content
   - Seeks back to the header position using absolute positioning
   - Overwrites the header with the actual value
   - Restores the write position to after the body

This pattern is commonly used when you need to write a header that contains information about the data that follows (like size or checksum), which you can only determine after writing the body.

